Another consumer product that has significantly altered our habits and routines by transitioning to electronic form is the digital camera. With traditional cameras, we lacked immediate feedback on photo quality, meticulously chose and shot scenes to conserve film, carried cumbersome rolls of film, and only saw the final results in printed form. In contrast, digital cameras resolve these issues and offer numerous additional features enabled by electronic processing, such as transmitting images via cellphones or retouching photos using computers. This section explores the functioning of digital cameras.

The camera's "front end" must convert light into electricity, a task handled by an array of "pixels." Each pixel comprises an electronic device called a "photodiode," which generates a current proportional to the light intensity it receives. As shown in Fig. 1.5(a), this current flows through a capacitance, $C_{L}$, for a specific duration, creating a corresponding voltage across it. Thus, each pixel produces a voltage proportional to the local light density.

Consider a camera with 6.25 million pixels arranged in a $2500 \times 2500$ array [Fig. 1.5(b)]. How are the output voltages of each pixel sensed and processed? If each pixel had its own electronic circuitry, the array would occupy a large area, increasing cost and power dissipation. Therefore, we "time-share" the signal processing circuits among pixels. To achieve this, we follow the circuit in Fig. 1.5(a) with a simple, compact amplifier and a switch (within the pixel) [Fig. 1.5(c)]. We then connect a wire to the outputs of all 2500 pixels in a "column," activate one switch at a time, and apply the corresponding voltage to the "signal processing" block outside the column.

