extrainfo:The circuit diagram shows a configuration where each OpAmp (A1 to A4) is connected to a diode and capacitor, forming a basic signal processing unit. These units are connected to switches (SW1 to SW4) that direct the processed signals to nodes X1 and X2. The signals from X1 and X2 are then fed into an ADC, which digitizes the analog signals. This setup allows sharing one ADC between two columns of a pixel array, optimizing the use of ADCs by time-sharing.

Figure 1.7 Sharing one ADC between two columns of a pixel array.

Once in the digital domain, the "video" signal collected by the camera can be extensively manipulated. For instance, to "zoom in," the digital signal processor (DSP) simply focuses on a section of the array, discarding information from the remaining pixels. Additionally, to reduce memory requirements, the processor "compresses" the video signal.

The digital camera exemplifies the extensive use of both analog and digital microelectronics. Analog functions include amplification, switching, and analog-to-digital conversion, while digital functions involve subsequent signal processing and storage.

Today's microelectronic systems integrate numerous analog functions. As demonstrated by the cellphone and digital camera examples discussed earlier, analog circuits often制约 the overall system performance.

The most prevalent analog function is amplification. The signal received by a cellphone or captured by a microphone is too weak for further processing. Consequently, an amplifier is essential to elevate the signal swing to acceptable levels.

Amplifier performance is evaluated based on several parameters, such as gain, speed, and power dissipation. We will delve into these aspects of amplification in detail later in this book, but it is beneficial to briefly review some of these concepts here.

A voltage amplifier generates an output swing that exceeds the input swing. The voltage gain, $A_{v}$, is defined as

$$
\begin{equation*}
A_{v}=\frac{v_{\text {out }}}{v_{\text {in }}} \tag{1.1}
\end{equation*}
$$

In certain instances, we opt to express the gain in decibels (dB):

$$
\begin{equation*}
\left.A_{v}\right|_{d B}=20 \log \frac{v_{\text {out }}}{v_{\text {in }}} \tag{1.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

For instance, a voltage gain of 10 equates to 20 dB. The gain of typical amplifiers ranges from $10^{1}$ to $10^{5}$.

Example: A cellphone receives a signal of $20 \mu \mathrm{~V}$, but it needs to deliver a swing of 50 mV to the 1.3 speaker for voice reproduction. Calculate the necessary voltage gain in decibels.

Solution:

$$
\begin{align*}
A_{v} & =20 \log \frac{50 \mathrm{mV}}{20 \mu \mathrm{~V}}  \tag{1.3}\\
& \approx 68 \mathrm{~dB} . \tag{1.4}
\end{align*}
$$

Exercise: Determine the output swing if the gain is 50 dB.

For an amplifier to function correctly and provide gain, it must draw power from a voltage source, such as a battery or charger. This source, termed the "power supply," is typically represented by $V_{C C}$ or $V_{D D}$ [Fig. 1.13(a)]. In intricate circuits, we may simplify the notation as shown in Fig. 1.13(b), where the "ground" terminal indicates a reference point with zero potential. If the amplifier is depicted by a triangle, we may even omit the supply terminals [Fig. 1.13(c)], understanding that they are present. Typical amplifiers operate with supply voltages ranging from 1 V to 10 V.
