$$
\begin{equation*}
\sum_{j} V_{j}=0 \tag{1.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $V_{j}$ denotes the voltage drop across element number $j$. KVL stems from the conservation of the "electromotive force." In the example illustrated in Fig. 1.19(a), we may sum the voltages in the loop to zero: $V_{1}+V_{2}+V_{3}+V_{4}=0$. Alternatively, adopting the modified view shown in Fig. 1.19(b), we can say $V_{1}$ is equal to the sum of the voltages across elements 2, 3, and 4: $V_{1}=V_{2}+V_{3}+V_{4}$. Note that the polarities assigned to $V_{2}$, $V_{3}$, and $V_{4}$ in Fig. 1.19(b) are different from those in Fig. 1.19(a).

