While Kirchoff's laws are always applicable for solving any circuit, Thevenin's and Norton's theorems offer a simplification of the algebraic process and, more significantly, provide deeper insights into circuit behavior.

Thevenin's theorem asserts that a linear one-port network can be substituted with an equivalent circuit consisting of a single voltage source in series with a single impedance. The term "port" refers to any two nodes where the voltage difference is of interest. The equivalent voltage, $v_{\text {Thev }}$, is determined by leaving the port open and calculating the voltage generated by the actual circuit at this port. The equivalent impedance, $Z_{\text {Thev }}$, is calculated by setting all independent voltage and current sources in the circuit to zero and measuring the impedance between the two nodes. We also refer to $Z_{\text {Thev }}$ as the impedance "seen" when "looking" into the output port. The impedance is determined by applying a voltage source across the port and measuring the resulting current. Several few examples will illustrate these principles.

Consider the input voltage source and the amplifier shown in Fig. 1.20, which are enclosed in a box, and only the output port is of interest. Determine the Thevenin equivalent of the circuit.

The Thevenin voltage is obtained from Fig. 1.24(a) and Eq. (1.9):

$$
\begin{align*}
v_{\text {Thev }} & =v_{\text {out }}  \tag{1.17}\\
& =-g_{m} R_{L} v_{\text {in }} . \tag{1.18}
\end{align*}
$$

To calculate $Z_{\text {Thev }}$, we set $v_{\text {in }}$ to zero, apply a voltage source, $v_{X}$, across the output port, and determine the current drawn from the voltage source, $i_{X}$. As shown in Fig. 1.24(b), setting $v_{\text {in }}$ to zero means replacing it with a short circuit. Also, note that the current source $g_{m} v_{\pi}$ remains in the circuit because it depends on the voltage across $r_{\pi}$, whose value is not known a priori.

How do we solve the circuit of Fig. 1.24(b)? We must again eliminate $v_{\pi}$. Fortunately, since both terminals of $r_{\pi}$ are tied to ground, $v_{\pi}=0$ and $g_{m} v_{\pi}=0$. The circuit thus reduces to $R_{L}$ and

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{X}=\frac{v_{X}}{R_{L}} \tag{1.19}
\end{equation*}
$$

That is,

$$
\begin{equation*}
R_{\text {Thev }}=R_{L} \tag{1.20}
\end{equation*}
$$

Figure 1.24(c) depicts the Thevenin equivalent of the input voltage source and the amplifier. In this case, we call $R_{\text {Thev }}\left(=R_{L}\right)$ the "output impedance" of the circuit.

With the Thevenin equivalent of a circuit available, we can readily analyze its behavior in the presence of a subsequent stage or "load."

Consider the amplifier of Fig. 1.20, which must drive a speaker having an impedance of $R_{s p}$. Determine the voltage delivered to the speaker.

Shown in Fig. 1.25(a) is the overall circuit arrangement that we must solve. Replacing the section in the dashed box with its Thevenin equivalent from Fig. 1.24(c), we greatly simplify the circuit [Fig. 1.25(b)], and write

$$
\begin{align*}
v_{\text {out }} & =-g_{m} R_{L} v_{\text {in }} \frac{R_{s p}}{R_{s p}+R_{L}}  \tag{1.21}\\
& =-g_{m} v_{\text {in }}\left(R_{L} \| R_{s p}\right) . \tag{1.22}
\end{align*}
$$

Norton's theorem states that a linear one-port network can be represented by a single current source in parallel with a single impedance. The equivalent current, $i_{\text {Nor }}$, is obtained by shorting the port of interest and calculating the current that flows through it. The equivalent impedance, $Z_{\mathrm{Nor}}$, is determined by setting all independent voltage and current sources in the circuit to zero and calculating the impedance seen at the port. Of course, $Z_{\text {Nor }}=Z_{\text {Thev }}$.

