Norton's theorem is a pivotal concept in electrical engineering that streamlines the analysis of intricate circuits. It posits that any linear one-port network can be substituted with a simplified equivalent circuit consisting of a single current source in parallel with a single impedance. This transformation is particularly useful when the circuit's interaction with an external load needs to be analyzed.

The equivalent current source, labeled as $i_{\text{Nor}}$, is identified by determining the current that flows through the port when it is short-circuited. This current is referred to as the short-circuit current of the network. The equivalent impedance, denoted as $Z_{\text{Nor}}$, is the impedance observed at the port when all independent sources within the network are deactivated, which is identical to the Thevenin equivalent impedance, $Z_{\text{Thev}}$. as both represent the network's impedance as seen from the port without any load connected.

Utilizing Norton's theorem allows engineers to convert a complex network into a more straightforward model, which is especially helpful for analyzing the network's behavior in conjunction with an external load. The Norton equivalent circuit can be employed to ascertain the voltage across or the current through the load, as well as other network responses, by applying fundamental circuit analysis techniques such as Ohm's law and Kirchhoff's laws.

In practical application, obtaining the Norton equivalent involves a two-step process:

1. Calculate the Norton current, $i_{\text{Nor}}$, by short-circuiting the output port and measuring the current that flows through the short circuit.
2. Determine the Norton impedance, $Z_{\text{Nor}}$, by deactivating all independent sources within the network and calculating the impedance seen looking into the port.

Once the Norton equivalent circuit is established, it can be used to predict the network's behavior under various loading conditions, simplifying the overall analysis process.
